  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Determine which of the following sets <m>W</m> is a subspace of <m>\R^n</m> for the indicated value of <m>n</m>.
        Justify your answer.
      </p>
    </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>W = \{[x \ 0]^{\tr} : x \text{ is a scalar } \}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>W = \{[2x+y \ x-y \ x+y]^{\tr} : x,y \text{ are scalars } \}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>W = \{[x+1 \ x-1]^{\tr} : x \text{ is a scalar } \}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>W = \{[xy \ xz \ yz ]^{\tr} : x,y,z \text{ are scalars } \}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
      
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find a subset of <m>\R^2</m> that is closed under addition and scalar multiplication,
        but that does not contain the zero vector,
        or explain why no such subset exists.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>\vv</m> be a vector in <m>\R^2</m>.
        What is the smallest subspace of <m>\R^2</m> that contains <m>\vv</m>?
        Explain.
        Describe this space geometrically.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        What is the smallest subspace of <m>\R^2</m> containing the first quadrant?
        Justify your answer.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Let <m>\vu</m>, <m>\vv</m>,
        and <m>\vw</m> be vectors in <m>\R^3</m> with <m>\vw = \vu+\vv</m>.
        Let <m>W_1 = \Span\{\vu,\vv\}</m> and <m>W_2 = \Span\{\vu,\vv,\vw\}</m>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If <m>\vx</m> is in <m>W_1</m>,
              must <m>\vx</m> be in <m>W_2</m>?
              Explain.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              If <m>\vy</m> is in <m>W_2</m>,
              must <m>\vy</m> be in <m>W_1</m>?
              Explain.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              What is the relationship between
              <m>\Span\{\vu,\vv\}</m> and <m>\Span\{\vu,\vv,\vw\}</m>?
              Be specific.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
      
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Let <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> be positive integers,
        and let <m>\vv</m> be in <m>\R^n</m>.
        Let <m>W = \{A\vv : A \in \M_{m \times n}\}</m>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
        <task>
          <introduction>
            <p>
              As an example,
              let <m>\vv = [2 \ 1]^{\tr}</m> in <m>\R^2</m> with <m>W = \{A\vv : A \in \M_{2 \times 2}\}</m>.
            </p>
          </introduction>
              <task>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Show that the vector <m>[2 \ 1]^{\tr}</m> is in <m>W</m> by finding a matrix <m>A</m> that places <m>[2 \ 1]^{\tr}</m> in <m>W</m>.
                  </p>
                </statement>
              </task>
              <task>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Show that the the vector <m>[4 \ 2]^{\tr}</m> is in <m>W</m> by finding a matrix <m>A</m> that places <m>[4 \ 2]^{\tr}</m> in <m>W</m>.
                  </p>
                </statement>
              </task>
              <task>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Show that the vector <m>[6 \ -1]^{\tr}</m> is in <m>W</m> by finding a matrix <m>A</m> that places <m>[6 \ -1]^{\tr}</m> in <m>W</m>.
                  </p>
                </statement>
              </task>
              <task>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Show that <m>W = \R^2</m>.
                  </p>
                </statement>
              </task>
            
          </task>
          <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Show that, regardless of the vector <m>\vv</m> selected,
              <m>W</m> is a subspace of <m>\R^m</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Characterize all of the possibilities for what the subspace <m>W</m> can be.
              
            </p>
          </statement>
          <hint>
            <p>
              There is more than one possibility.
            </p>
          </hint>
        </task>
      
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>S_1</m> and <m>S_2</m> be subsets of <m>\R^3</m> such that <m>\Span \ S_1 = \Span \ S_2</m>.
        Must it be the case that <m>S_1</m> and <m>S_2</m> contain at least one vector in common?
        Justify your answer.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Assume <m>W_1</m> and <m>W_2</m> are two subspaces of <m>\R^n</m>.
        Is <m>W_1 \cap W_2</m> also a subspace of <m>\R^n</m>?
        Is <m>W_1 \cup W_2</m> also a subspace of <m>\R^n</m>?
        Justify your answer.
        (Note: The notation <m>W_1 \cap W_2</m> refers to the vectors common to both <m>W_1, W_2</m>,
        while the notation <m>W_1 \cup W_2</m> refers to the vectors that are in at least one of <m>W_1, W_2</m>.)
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Determine whether the plane defined by the equation
        <m>5x+3y-2z=0</m> is a subspace in <m>\R^3</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>W</m> is a subspace of <m>\R^n</m> and <m>\vu</m> is a vector in <m>\R^n</m> not in <m>W</m>,
        determine whether
        <me>
          \vu+W = \{\vu+\vv: \vv \text{ is a vector in } W\}
        </me>
        is a subspace of <m>\R^n</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Two students are talking about examples of subspaces.
        <blockquote>
          Student 1: The <m>x</m>-axis in <m>\R^2</m> is a subspace. It is generated by the vector <m>\left[ \begin{array}{c} 1\\0 \end{array} \right]</m>.
        </blockquote>
        <blockquote>
          Student 2: Similarly <m>\R^2</m> is a subspace of <m>\R^3</m>.
        </blockquote>
        <blockquote>
          Student 1: I'm not sure if that will work. Can we fit <m>\R^2</m> inside <m>\R^3</m>? Don't we need <m>W</m> to be a subset of <m>\R^3</m> if it is a subspace of <m>\R^3</m>?
        </blockquote>
        <blockquote>
          Student 2: Of course we can fit <m>\R^2</m> inside <m>\R^3</m>. We can think of <m>\R^2</m> as vectors <m>\left[ \begin{array}{c} a\\b\\0 \end{array} \right]</m>. That's the <m>xy</m>-plane.
        </blockquote>
        <blockquote>
          Student 1: I don't know. The vector <m>\left[ \begin{array}{c} a\\b\\0 \end{array} \right]</m> is not exactly same as <m>\left[ \begin{array}{c} a\\b \end{array} \right]</m>.
        </blockquote>
        <blockquote>
          Student 2: Well, <m>\R^2</m> is a plane and so is the <m>xy</m>-plane. So they must be equal, shouldn't they?
        </blockquote>
        <blockquote>
          Student 1: But there are infinitely many planes in <m>\R^3</m>. They can't all be equal to <m>\R^2</m>. They all
          <q>look like</q>
          <m>\R^2</m> but I don't think we can say they are equal.
        </blockquote>
        Which student is correct?
        Is <m>\R^2</m> a subspace of <m>\R^3</m>, or not?
        Justify your answer.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

